lars from the United States and Europe. Divided into three sections, the book first establishes the notion of the flesh as a consistent concept and unfolds the nuances of flesh that make it a compelling idea. The second section adds to the force of this idea by showing how flesh can be extended to phenomena that Merleau-Ponty was not able to treat, such as the internet and virtual reality, and the third offers criticisms of Merleau-Ponty from feminist and Levinasian points of view. All the essays attest to the fecundity of Merleau-Ponty's later thought for such central philosophical issues as the bonds between self, others, and the world.Contributors include Renaud Barbaras, Mauro Carbone, Edward S. Casey, Suzanne L. Cataldi, Tina Chanter, Françoise Dastur, Jean Greisch, Lawrence Hass, Marjorie Hass, James Hatley, Henri Maldiney, Linda Martin Alcoff, Berhard Waldenfels, Gail Weiss, Hugh J. Silverman, and Edith Wyschogrod.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aAlcoff, Linda Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbaras, Renaud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbone, Mauro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Edward S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCataldi, Suzanne Laba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDastur, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Fred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1